	abstract = {Background
Many studies have reported associations between ambient particulate matter ({PM}) and adverse health effects, focused on either short-term (acute) or long-term (chronic) {PM} exposures. For chronic effects, the studied cohorts have rarely been representative of the population. We present a novel exposure model combining satellite aerosol optical depth and land-use data to investigate both the long- and short-term effects of {PM}2.5 exposures on population mortality in Massachusetts, United States, for the years 2000–2008.

Methods
